{{for|the ''V for Vendetta'' character|V for Vendetta}}
{{Infobox person | name = Conrad Heyer | image = Conrad Heyer (1852).jpg | alt = A black-and-white photo of Heyer's face | caption = Conrad Heyer, photographed in 1852, aged 103 | birth_date = {{Circa}} 1749 | birth_place = [[Waldoboro]], [[Maine]], [[Province of Massachusetts Bay]], [[British America]] | death_date = {{Death year and age|1856|1749}} | death_place = Waldoboro, Maine, [[United States]] |known_for = {{bulleted list|Earliest-born known human photographed|Only known photographed person to have [[Washington's crossing of the Delaware|crossed the Delaware]] with [[George Washington]]}} }}
'''Conrad Heyer''' (1749–1856) was an [[United States|American]] farmer and veteran of the [[American Revolutionary War|Revolutionary War]] who is notable for possibly being the earliest-born American to have been [[History of photography|photographed]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Schultz|first1=Colin|title=Conrad Heyer, a Revolutionary War Veteran, Was the Earliest-Born American To Ever Be Photographed|url=http://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/conrad-heyer-a-revolutionary-war-veteran-was-the-earliest-born-american-to-ever-be-photographed-180947660/|accessdate=15 August 2015|date=2013-11-11}}</ref>
== Biography ==
Heyer was born in the village of [[Waldoboro]], [[Maine]], then known as "Broad Bay" and part of the [[Province of Massachusetts Bay]]. The settlement had been [[Northeast Coast Campaign (1746)|sacked and depopulated]] by [[Wabanaki Confederacy|Wabanaki]] attacks and resettled with [[German Americans|German immigrants]] recruited from the [[Rhineland]]. Among these settlers were the parents of Conrad Heyer, who also may have been the [[first white child]] born in the settlement.<ref name="New Market Press">{{cite web|url=http://www.newmarketpressvt.com/news/2013/jul/25/new-england-man-had-oldest-birth-date-ever-be-phot/|title=New England man had oldest birth date ever to be photographed|accessdate=18 October 2015|author=New Market Press|date=25 July 2013|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20131117201704/http://www.newmarketpressvt.com/news/2013/jul/25/new-england-man-had-oldest-birth-date-ever-be-phot/|archivedate=17 November 2013}}</ref>
During the [[American Revolution]], Heyer fought for the [[Continental Army]] under the command of [[George Washington]] and participated in Washington's famous [[Washington's crossing of the Delaware|crossing of the Delaware]] before the [[Battle of Trenton]] in December 1776.<ref name="New Market Press" /> He was discharged in December 1777.<ref name="Maine HS">{{cite web|url=https://www.mainememory.net/artifact/13423|title=Conrad Heyer, Waldoboro, ca. 1852|accessdate=12 April 2018|author=Maine Historical Society}}</ref> After the war, he returned to Waldoboro, where he made a living as a farmer until his death in 1856. He was buried with full military honors.<ref name="Maine HS" />
In 1852, at the age of 103, Heyer posed for a [[daguerreotype]] portrait. He thereby became the earliest-born person of whom a photograph is known to exist.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Frank|first1=Priscilla|title=This Is Conrad Hayer, A Man Who Made Photographic History At 103 Years Old|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/05/27/oldest-person-photographe_n_5366765.html|accessdate=15 August 2015|date=2014-05-27}}</ref> The claim is not without dispute, as the following men were also photographed: a shoemaker named John Adams, who claimed to be born in 1745; a Revolutionary War veteran named Baltus Stone, with a claim of 1744; and a slave named Caesar, with a claim of 1738.<ref name="First photo">{{cite web|url=http://benbeck.co.uk/firsts/2_The_Human_Subject/photo1h.htm|title=First photo|accessdate=12 April 2018|last1=Beck|first1=Benjamin}}</ref>
